      <scopecontent id="aspace_82ce0f0dad2490d6b86b24ac8e5859e9">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The Edward Livingston Wells Papers are contained in one box and were given to Yale University by Lewis Perry Curtis in 1944.</p>
         <p>The Papers primarily consist of lectures on Genesis (folders 2-10), sermons (folders 11-13), and student notes (folders 14-23). The lectures on Genesis I:1-31 were given between January and March 1856. Manuscripts of five sermons are included, among them Wells' first sermon, written in French, while he was attending the Protestant Theological Seminary of Montauban, France, and an anniversary sermon from Matthew VII:20. The student notes are all written in French and cover religious topics.</p>
         <p>For additional information on the life of Edward Livingston Wells see the Lewis Perry Curtis Family Papers, Manuscript Group Number 587, Series IV.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <bioghist id="aspace_c9ee244e6a339035aba429d8e62d7c9c">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Edward Livingston Wells was born in Columbia, South Carolina, in 1834. He studied theology in Pau, France and graduated with high honors. Returning to the United States, he began preaching at a Congregational church in Plainvill, Connecticut. He moved to the Episcopal church in 1859 and in 1860, was ordained to the priesthood. He would also preach in Louisville, Kentucky, Pittsfield, Massachusetts, and Southport, Connecticut. In this latter town, he and his wife, Mary Huder Hughes, had several children. He died in New Milford, Connecticut, in 1880.</p>  
      </bioghist>
